6.2 Autocorrelation & Partial Autocorrelation Function¶

In order to indicate which past series values are more useful to predict future values, we are going to apply both functions Autocorrelation & Partial Autocorrelation to analyse the correlation between the values of our dependent variable (demand).

In [5]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

plot_acf(df['Demand'], lags=100)  
plt.show()

plot_pacf(df['Demand'])
plt.show()
  • Autocorrelation: In this plot we can observe that our dependent variable is autocorrelated roughly up to 40 lags.
  • Partial Autocorrelation: In this graph, there is a significant correlation at lag 1 followed by some positive correlations that are lower. So, we are going to use 1 lag before to fit our prediction model ARIMA.

The results show that we have enough correlation between the values of the variable demand and this justifies our choice of ARIMA model.

6.4 Seasonal Decomposition¶

In this part we are going to decompose our data in there components which are:

  • Original: It is the main value that goes on average with time (The evolution of demand before we decompose it).
  • Trend: The trend is the value that causes increasing or decreasing patterns in a time series.
  • Seasonality: This is a cyclic event that occurs in time series for a short time and causes the increasing or decreasing patterns for a short time in a time series.
  • residuals: These are the random variations in the time series (residuals = Original - Trend - Seasonality).

In order to apply this decomposition we are going to work with period of 30 days

In [7]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

decomposition = seasonal_decompose(df["Demand"].dropna(), period = 30)

trend = decomposition.trend
seasonal = decomposition.seasonal
residual = decomposition.resid

6.5 Check for stationarity¶

Stationarity means that wherever you are in your time of your variable you have the same mean and the same variance (dispersion around the mean). It is important beacause if your distribution is changing over time, it gets difficult to forecast.
In [10]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
dftest = adfuller(df['Demand'], autolag='AIC')
dftest

Test of stationarity using Dickey-Fuller¶

In [11]:
#Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
def test_stationarity(timeseries):    
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items(): # key, value mapping
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput)
    if dftest[0] < dftest[4]["5%"]:
        print ("Reject Ho - Time Series is Stationary")
    else:
        print ("Failed to Reject Ho - Time Series is Non-Stationary")

6.6 Applying ARIMA model¶

As we have explained, we are going to use ARIMA model to be able to predict the dependent variable demand based only on itself. We are making a one-day-ahead forecast because the ARIMA is retrained before every forecast.

In [17]:
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

from statsmodels.tsa.arima_model import ARIMA

X = df["Demand"].values
size = 756

# walk forward validation: train the whole model! at each iteration including the new observation (for the next day)
train, test = X[0:size], X[size:len(X)] # [0:756][756:786]

history = [x for x in train] # "list comprehensions". 
expect=[]

predictions = list()
for t in range(len(test)): # 10 times reiterate
    model = ARIMA(history, order=(2,1,0)) # and 10
    model_fit = model.fit(disp=0)
    output = model_fit.forecast()
    yhat = output[0]
    predictions.append(yhat)
    obs = test[t]
    history.append(obs) # appends the real observation at each loop! 
    expect.append(obs)

Calculating the RMSE of our ARIMA model¶

In [20]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
def forecast_accuracy(forecast, actual):
    #rmse = np.mean((forecast - actual)**2)**.5  # RMSE
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(forecast, actual))
    return({'rmse':rmse})

def adjust(val, length= 10): return str(val).ljust(length) # 10
print('Forecast Accuracy of: Demand')
accuracy_prod = forecast_accuracy(df_Demand['forecast'].values, df_Demand['observations'].values)
for k, v in accuracy_prod.items():
    print(adjust(k), ': ', round(v,4))

The plot is showing a hudge difference between the actual and the predicted demand. Maybe we didn't apply the optimal lags. That is why, in the following command, we are going to check different lags to conclude which number is the optimal to work with.

In [39]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
X = df["Demand"].values
# evaluate an ARIMA model for a given order (p,d,q)
def evaluate_arima_model(X, arima_order):
# prepare training dataset
    train_size = int(len(X) * 0.95)
    train, test = X[0:train_size], X[train_size:]
    history = [x for x in train]
    # make predictions
    predictions = list()
    for t in range(len(test)):
        model = ARIMA(history, order=arima_order)
        model_fit = model.fit()
        yhat = model_fit.forecast()[0]
        predictions.append(yhat)
        history.append(test[t])
    # calculate out of sample error
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test, predictions))
    return rmse
In [42]:
# evaluate combinations of p, d and q values for an ARIMA model
def evaluate_models(dataset, p_values, d_values, q_values):
    dataset = dataset.astype('float32')
    best_score, best_cfg = float("inf"), None
    for p in p_values:
        for d in d_values:
            for q in q_values:
                order = (p,d,q)
                try:
                    rmse = evaluate_arima_model(dataset, order)
                    if rmse < best_score:
                        best_score, best_cfg = rmse, order
                    print('ARIMA%s RMSE=%.3f' % (order,rmse))
                except:
                    continue
    print('Best ARIMA%s RMSE=%.3f' % (best_cfg, best_score))

7 Conclusion¶

To conclude, in the EDA part, we were able to analyze the demand in a detailed way taking into account several variables in our data frame. Theoretically, we believed that there will be some relationship or correlation between our dependent variable and the rest of the variables chosen as predictors. However, the heat map gave us quite different results showing a very low correlation between the variables, which is why we opted for the ARIMA method to forecast the demand by itself.

Following the results of our ARIMA model, we found that the demand, in our specific case, is not forecastable. But, we can explain this by the fact that our data set only includes data from the second half of 2015 until the first half of 2017. So, we can say that we didn't have enough data that allows a good learning of the model. It is possible that we would have had quite different and rather positive results if we had used a much richer data set that contains data of several complete years. Or, we may not be able to predict the demand using the ARIMA model because it doesn't forecast correctly the direction of the demand and just coping the past.

For this reason, in order to improve the answer to our problematic question, it is recommended to test other models to reach the final conclusion whether the demand is actually forecastable or not.
